[1] Chile (Bio-Bio)
Date: Fri 12 Aug 2011
Source: Publimetro [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://www.publimetro.cl/nota/cronica/ministerio-de-salud-decreta-alerta-sanitaria-en-region-del-biobio-por-hanta-virus/CPIkhl!XYcxs5xD7PsYXUqt5mbs9Q/


The Chile Ministry of Health decided to decree a health alert in the
Bio-Bio region when 8 cases of [a] hantavirus [infection] were
confirmed. The cardiopulmonary syndrome is attributed to the explosive
increase of long tailed [pygmy rice] rats [_Oligoryzomys
longicaudatus_], the main transmitters of the disease [virus].

Thus, 3 regions can count on of additional resources to confront the
implications of this public health problem, since the branch of the
Ministry decreed the same measure in Los Lagos and Aysen. The decision
was taken as a preventive measure, "with the objective of avoiding the
spread of the virus in the area," stated the Subsecretary of Public
Health, Jorge Diaz, attending the laboratory of the Institute of
Public Health this Friday [12 Aug 2011].

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The hantavirus responsible for these cases and those reported below
in Chile is not mentioned, but is almost certain to be Andes virus.

An image of the long-tailed pygmy rice rat (_Oligoryzomys
longicaudatus_), the sigmodontine rodent host of Andes hantavirus, can
be seen at http://www.bios.niu.edu/frayjorge/rod6.jpg.

The regions of Chile can be seen on the map at
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Administrative_divisions_of_Chile. A
HealthMap/ProMED-mail map showing the location of the Bio-Bio region
can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/006H. - Mod.TY]

