[5] Paraguay (Boqueron)
Date: Sat 6 Aug 2011
Source: ABC Digital [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
http://www.abc.com.py/nota/el-hantavirus-mato-a-seis-personas-de-localidades-del-dpto-de-boqueron/


Between 20 Jan and 3 Aug [2011], 11 people were confirmed with
hantavirus [infections] and one more is awaiting confirmation; of
these, 6 people died, which signifies a 55 percent fatality rate. Dr
Silvio Ortega, Director of the XVII Sanitary Region, indicated that
the cases were from different localities of Boqueron department, but
most of them were from Chaco Central [region] or nearby. To date,
there are no reports of various cases in just one place.

The physician indicated that the cases are always related to crops of
peanuts and sorghum, "as a relevant fact, the great deforestation that
can be seen in different places, which we think is the cause of
dispersion of mice (_Calomys laucha_)."

Lic. Hugo Paredes stated that as much as possible they will intervene
in places where infection occurred to search for more suspected cases
and to inform the public about preventive measures.

[Byline: Marvin Duerksen]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-ESP
<promed-esp@promedmail.org>

The hantaviruses involved in these cases and those reported below are
not specified. The 21 Jul 2011 ProMED post (archive no. 20110721.2196)
reported that in 2008, in the Boqueron department, there was a
hantavirus epidemic and the year ended with about 30 cases and 4
deaths. At that time, the health authorities attributed the outbreak
in the Chaco region to environmental problems from deforestation of
the region, constant fires, and land clearing that favored the
urbanization of rats, carriers of the virus that causes the disease,
in the communities.

_Calomys laucha_, a rural rodent common in central Chaco areas, is the
one that transmits Laguna Negra hantavirus, according to Paraguay's
Health Surveillance director Dr Ivan Allende. However, in addition to
Laguna Negra virus, other hantaviruses that can cause HPS (hantavirus
pulmonary syndrome) and are found in Paraguay (and their rodent
hosts), from a list kindly provided by Dr James Mills, include Bermejo
(_Oligoryzomys chacoensis_), Lechiguanas (_Oligoryzomys flavescens_),
Central Plata (_Oligoryzomys flavescens_), Anajatuba (possible HPS;
_Oligoryzomys fornesi_), Oran (__Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_), and
Juquitiba (__Oligoryzomys nigripes_).

An image of _Calomys laucha_ can be accessed at
http://www.faunaparaguay.com/Calomys%20laucha%20www.pybio.org.jpg.

A map showing the departments of Paraguay can be seen at
http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/paraguay.pdf. A
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map showing the location of Boqueron
department can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/18j3. -
Mod.TY]

******
[6] Paraguay (Itapua)
Date: Sun 7 Aug 2011
Source: Iguazu Noticias [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
http://iguazunoticias.com/v2011beta/?p=9756


The 1st locally acquired case of [a] hantavirus [infection] in the
Itapua department was detected in a 28-year-old patient resident of
the General Delgado locality, as was confirmed by local health
authorities. The patient is currently in stable condition, admitted to
the Encarnacion Regional Hospital, after intensive treatment in the
Instituto de Prevision Social [Institute of Social Welfare]. This case
has no relation to the Chaco [region -- see [5] above], where an
outbreak of the disease was registered.

"Yesterday [6 Aug 2011] a team from the regional unit went there with
epidemiologists, physicians, and officials from SENAPA [Servicio
Nacional de Erradicacion del Paludismo; National Service for the
Eradication of Malaria], although in reality SENAPA is not in charge
of rodent issues. They went there to do collect data on where the
patient was working, to look for other people who might be suspected
of having the disease, and to look for any connection as to how this
happened," stated Dr Jose Antonio Rolon, Director of the 7th Health
Region.

The official confirmed that the patient is the 1st locally acquired
hantavirus [infection] case in Itapua department, where 3 cases were
detected in 2005 and 2006, [but] all were imported from other areas of
the country.

